				\begin{document}$${E}_{RHE}={E}_{Ag/AgCl}+0.059\times pH+0.197$$\end{document}All the measurements were performed with iR compensation except for the chronopotentiometric tests.

The hybrid seawater electrolyzer was assembled by using a homemade two-electrode flow cell with NiCo@C/MXene/CF with the same area as the identical anode and cathode. The seawater containing 1.0 M KOH or neutral seawater was used as the catholyte while 1.0 M KOH with 0.5 M hydrazine was fed as the anolyte, which were cycled by the peristaltic pumps (Longer, BT100-2J). The cathode and anode chambers were separated by an anion exchange membrane (Fumasep FAA-3-PK-130). The electrolysis tests were performed on a CHI 760E electrochemical workstation. The polarization curves were measured at a scan rate of 10 mV s–1 with iR compensation. The stability test was carried out at the controlled current densities. The gas products from the cells were collected and examined by gas chromatography (GC, Agilent Technologies 7890 N). Meanwhile, the theoretical amount of evolved gas can be calculated by the equation:2N=I×t/(n×F)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
